MASTER SYLLABUS: SILICON ENGINEERING & RTL/DV
Target Roles: ASIC Design Engineer, RTL Engineer, Design Verification (DV) Engineer, SoC Architect.
Target Companies: Qualcomm, Google Silicon, Nvidia, AMD, Intel, SiTime, Synopsys, Cadence.

MODULE 1: Advanced Digital Logic & Arithmetic (The RTL Core)
This section tests your ability to think in hardware, not software.
1.1 Combinational Logic Design
Multiplexers (MUX): Building universal logic gates using 2:1 MUXes. Shannon Expansion theorem for mapping complex boolean functions to MUX trees.
Decoders & Encoders: Priority encoders, address decoding for memory maps.
Logic Minimization: K-Maps, Quine-McCluskey method, handling "Don't Care" conditions to optimize hardware footprint.
1.2 Digital Arithmetic (High-Performance Datapaths)
Adders: Ripple Carry Adder (RCA), Carry Lookahead Adder (CLA - master the generate/propagate equations), Carry Save Adder (CSA), Carry Select Adder.
Multipliers: Array multipliers, Radix-4 Booth Encoding Multiplier (industry standard for signed multiplication), Wallace Tree multipliers.
Dividers: Restoring vs. Non-Restoring division architectures.
1.3 Sequential Logic Design
Latches vs. Flip-Flops: Deep understanding of Master-Slave D-Flip Flop architecture. Why latches cause timing issues in modern RTL.
Flip-Flop Conversions: Converting D-FF to T-FF, JK-FF, or SR-FF using combinational logic.
Counters: Synchronous vs. Asynchronous (Ripple) counters. Ring counters, Johnson counters, Modulo-N counters.
Clock Dividers: Designing Divide-by-2, Divide-by-3, and Fractional/Odd Clock Dividers (e.g., Divide-by-1.5) using 50% duty cycles.
1.4 Finite State Machines (FSM)
Architectures: Mealy vs. Moore machines (timing differences, output glitches).
State Encoding: Binary, Gray, and One-Hot encoding. (Know the area/speed trade-offs of each).
State Minimization: Removing redundant states to save Flip-Flops.
Sequence Detectors: Designing overlapping and non-overlapping sequence detectors (e.g., "Detect 10110").
FSMD: Finite State Machine with Datapath (separating control logic from arithmetic logic).

MODULE 2: Static Timing Analysis (STA) & CDC
This is the most heavily tested topic in Qualcomm and Google technical interviews.
2.1 Core STA Fundamentals
Timing Equations: Calculating Setup Time (Max Delay) and Hold Time (Min Delay).
Frequency: Calculating maximum operating frequency ($F_{max}$) based on propagation delay, setup time, and clock-to-Q delay.
Slack: Calculating Data Arrival Time, Data Required Time, Setup Slack, and Hold Slack.
2.2 Advanced Timing Concepts
Clock Skew & Jitter: How positive and negative clock skew mathematically impacts setup and hold equations.
Timing Violations: Strategies to fix Setup violations (logic pipelining, architectural redesign) and Hold violations (buffer insertion).
Path Types: Multi-cycle paths, False paths, Half-cycle paths (using falling-edge flops). On-Chip Variation (OCV).
2.3 Clock Domain Crossing (CDC)
Metastability: Definition, causes, and MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures).
Single-Bit CDC: Fast-to-Slow and Slow-to-Fast domain crossing. 2-Flop and 3-Flop synchronizer chains.
Multi-Bit CDC (Data Bus): Handshaking protocols (Req/Ack).
Asynchronous FIFOs: The ultimate interview question. Master the architecture, Dual-Port RAM, Gray code pointer conversion, and synchronization logic for generating Full and Empty flags safely.

MODULE 3: Computer Microarchitecture (The SoC CPU)
Crucial for Google and any SoC team.
3.1 Pipelining
The 5-Stage RISC: Instruction Fetch, Decode, Execute, Memory, Write-Back.
Hazards: Structural, Data (RAW, WAR, WAW), and Control hazards.
Hazard Resolution: Data forwarding (bypassing paths), pipeline interlocking (stalling/bubbles), pipeline flushing.
3.2 Advanced Processor Design
Instruction Level Parallelism (ILP): Superscalar architectures, VLIW.
Out-of-Order (OoO) Execution: Tomasulo’s Algorithm, Reservation Stations, Reorder Buffer (ROB) for precise exceptions.
Register Renaming: Eliminating false data dependencies (WAR/WAW).
Branch Prediction: Static vs. Dynamic prediction, 1-bit and 2-bit saturating counters, Branch Target Buffers (BTB).
3.3 Memory Hierarchy
Caches: Direct-Mapped, Set-Associative, Fully Associative.
Cache Misses: Compulsory (Cold), Capacity, Conflict.
Cache Replacement: LRU (Least Recently Used) policies.
Cache Coherence: The MESI Protocol (Modified, Exclusive, Shared, Invalid) for multi-core processors.
Virtual Memory: Page tables, TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer), page faults.

MODULE 4: Hardware Description Languages (Verilog)
You must write code that synthesizes into actual silicon.
4.1 Verilog Fundamentals
Assignments: Blocking (=) vs. Non-Blocking (<=). Race conditions in simulation.
Hardware Inference: Knowing exactly what Verilog code maps to a MUX, a Latch, or a Flip-Flop.
Latches: How incomplete if-else or case statements infer unwanted latches, and how to avoid them.
4.2 Advanced RTL Coding
FSM Coding Styles: 1-always block, 2-always block, and 3-always block styles (and why 3-block is preferred for Mealy/Moore separation).
Parameterized Design: Using parameter, localparam, and generate blocks for scalable hardware (e.g., parameterized FIFO depth).

MODULE 5: Verification (SystemVerilog & UVM)
The off-campus golden ticket. Master this to bypass the CGPA filter.
5.1 SystemVerilog Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
OOP Basics: Classes, objects, handles, constructors (new()).
Advanced OOP: Inheritance, Polymorphism, Virtual methods, pure virtual classes.
Factory Pattern: Concept of overriding object creation dynamically.
5.2 Randomization & Constraints
Methods: rand vs randc (cyclic).
Constraints: Constraint blocks, solve...before blocks, inline constraints (with), implication constraints (->), soft constraints.
Hooks: Using pre_randomize() and post_randomize().
5.3 Coverage
Code Coverage: Line, Toggle, Statement, FSM, and Branch coverage.
Functional Coverage: Writing covergroups, coverpoints, bins, illegal_bins, ignore_bins, and cross coverage to prove test completeness.
5.4 SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA)
Types: Immediate vs. Concurrent Assertions.
Syntax: Sequences, properties, implication operators (|-> overlapping, |=> non-overlapping).
Timing: Repetition operators (e.g., [*3], [1:$]), $past, $rose, $fell.
5.5 Universal Verification Methodology (UVM)
UVM Hierarchy: Env, Agent, Driver, Sequencer, Monitor, Scoreboard.
UVM Phases: Build, Connect, Run (task), Extract, Report.
Communication: TLM (Transaction Level Modeling) ports and exports, uvm_config_db.
Transactions: Sequences vs. Sequence Items.

MODULE 6: Industry Standard Protocols
To prove you can integrate your logic into a real-world SoC.
6.1 AMBA Architecture (ARM)
APB (Advanced Peripheral Bus): Non-pipelined, setup/access phases, used for control registers.
AHB (Advanced High-performance Bus): Pipelined address/data phases.
AXI4 (Advanced eXtensible Interface): Must Master. 5 independent channels, VALID/READY handshake rules, Burst modes (INCR, WRAP, FIXED), outstanding transactions, out-of-order completion.
6.2 Serial Communication
UART: Baud rate generation, 16x oversampling, parity generation/checking.
I2C: Multi-master arbitration, clock stretching, open-drain architecture.
SPI: Master/Slave setup, CPOL (Clock Polarity) and CPHA (Clock Phase) modes.

MODULE 7: Transistor-Level CMOS & Device Physics
Crucial for Qualcomm hardware roles.
7.1 MOSFET Physics
Regions: Cutoff, Linear (Triode), Saturation. Voltage equations for each.
Second-Order Effects: Channel Length Modulation (CLM), Body Effect, Velocity Saturation, Subthreshold Leakage.
Parasitics: Gate, source, drain, and body capacitances ($C_{gs}, C_{gd}$, etc.).
Advanced Nodes: Planar MOSFET vs. FinFET vs. Gate-All-Around (GAA).
7.2 The CMOS Inverter
VTC (Voltage Transfer Characteristic): Drawing the curve, understanding the operating regions of PMOS/NMOS at every point.
Metrics: Noise Margins ($NM_H, NM_L$), Switching Threshold ($V_M$).
Sizing: Why PMOS is sized 2x-3x larger than NMOS (mobility difference) for equal rise/fall times.
Logical Effort: Method for sizing a chain of logic gates to drive a massive capacitive load with minimum delay.
7.3 Memory Cells
6T SRAM: Schematic, Read operation, Write operation, Cell sizing (pull-up vs access vs pull-down ratios), Static Noise Margin (SNM).
DRAM: 1T1C (1-Transistor, 1-Capacitor) architecture, refresh cycles.
7.4 Low Power VLSI Design
Power Equations: Dynamic ($P = \alpha C V^2 f$), Short-Circuit, and Static (Leakage) power.
Architectural Reduction: Clock gating, Power gating (sleep transistors), Multi-VDD, Multi-Vt (threshold) libraries, DVFS (Dynamic Voltage & Frequency Scaling).

MODULE 8: Physical Design & DFT (Backend Basics)
You don't need to be an expert, but you must know the terminology.
Synthesis: Translating RTL to gate-level netlists.
SDC Constraints: Writing Synopsys Design Constraints (create_clock, set_input_delay, set_output_delay).
Design For Testability (DFT): Why we test silicon. Scan chains, stuck-at-0/stuck-at-1 fault models, Boundary Scan (JTAG), BIST (Built-In Self Test for memories).

MODULE 9: Programming, Scripting & Puzzles
The "Software Tools" and "Hidden Filter" rounds.
C/C++: Pointers, memory allocation. Bitwise Hacks (toggling bits, setting/clearing the nth bit, counting set bits). Basic Linked Lists and Queues.
Scripting: Basic Python or Perl/Tcl. Know how to open a log file, parse it for the word "Error", and output the results.
Digital Puzzles: Logic riddles, probability, sequence prediction, and designing arbitrary logic using only 2:1 multiplexers. (Practice GeeksforGeeks / BrainStellar).

