MODULE 10: Analog & Mixed-Signal IC Design (The Physical Foundation)
Tested heavily in written rounds and foundational technical interviews to filter out candidates who only understand code and not hardware.
10.1 Network Theory & Transients (The Written Test Filter)
RC & RL Circuits: This is guaranteed to be on the Qualcomm written test. You must be able to perform transient analysis by inspection (finding $V(0)$, $V(\infty)$, and $\tau$).
Frequency Response: Drawing and interpreting Bode plots (Magnitude and Phase). Identifying the -3dB cutoff frequency.
Resonance: Series and parallel RLC circuits, calculating the resonant frequency $f = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{LC}}$ and Quality Factor (Q).
Theorems: Thevenin and Norton equivalent circuits, Maximum Power Transfer theorem.
10.2 Operational Amplifiers (Op-Amps)
Ideal vs. Non-Ideal: Knowing the difference between an ideal Op-Amp (infinite input impedance, zero output impedance, infinite gain) and a real one.
Configurations: Inverting, Non-Inverting, Integrator, Differentiator, Summing, and Difference amplifiers.
Real-World Metrics: * CMRR (Common-Mode Rejection Ratio): Why it is critical for differential signaling.
Slew Rate: How fast the output can change ($dV/dt$). How it limits high-frequency large-signal operation.
Gain-Bandwidth Product (GBW): Understanding the trade-off between amplification and speed.
Virtual Short/Ground: Knowing when and why you can assume the two input terminals are at the same voltage (negative feedback).
10.3 Single-Stage Amplifiers & Biasing (Transistor-Level Analog)
Current Mirrors: The foundation of IC biasing. Simple current mirror, Cascode current mirror (used to increase output impedance $r_o$ and improve accuracy), and Widlar current source.
Amplifier Topologies (MOSFET):
Common Source (CS): High voltage gain, used as the main gain stage.
Common Drain (Source Follower): Voltage gain $\approx 1$, low output impedance, used as a voltage buffer.
Common Gate (CG): Low input impedance, used as a current buffer.
Differential Amplifiers: Tail current sources, common-mode vs. differential-mode gain.
The Miller Effect: How parasitic feedback capacitance ($C_{gd}$) is multiplied by the amplifier's gain, severely degrading high-frequency performance.
10.4 Mixed-Signal Building Blocks
Phase-Locked Loops (PLL): You must be able to draw the block diagram.
Components: Phase Detector (PD), Charge Pump (CP), Loop Filter (LPF), Voltage Controlled Oscillator (VCO), and Frequency Divider.
Concepts: Lock time, jitter, and how a PLL is used to multiply a low-frequency crystal clock up to a multi-GHz processor clock.
Oscillators: * Barkhausen Criterion: The two rules for sustained oscillation (Loop gain $\ge 1$, Phase shift $= 360^\circ$ or $0^\circ$).
Ring Oscillators: Delay calculation based on the number of stages (must be an odd number of inverters).
LC & Crystal Oscillators: High-Q oscillators used for stable timing (critical for companies like SiTime).
Data Converters (High-Level):
ADCs (Analog-to-Digital): Flash ADC (fastest, high area), SAR ADC (Successive Approximation Register - good balance of speed/power), Delta-Sigma ADC (high resolution, low speed).
DACs (Digital-to-Analog): R-2R ladder, Current-steering DACs. Quantization noise and resolution.
