Based on the job descriptions provided and the historical data of on-campus interview experiences for fresh graduates at Google (Silicon/Hardware) and Qualcomm (Hardware/SoC), the interview process is rigorously focused on fundamentals.
Companies like Google and Qualcomm do not expect a fresh graduate to know proprietary SoC architectures, but they expect absolute perfection in digital logic, timing, and basic microarchitecture.
Here is a breakdown of what to expect, followed by the "No Blindspot" syllabus.
Part 1: On-Campus Interview Experiences & Structure
Qualcomm (Usually 1 Written + 2-3 Technical + 1 HR)
The Written Test: This is often the biggest filter. It covers Aptitude, C Programming (pointers, bitwise operators), Digital Electronics, Network Theory (RC circuits), and basic CMOS.
Technical Rounds: Qualcomm heavily emphasizes Static Timing Analysis (STA) and CMOS fundamentals. You will be asked to draw CMOS gates at the transistor level, calculate RC delays, and solve complex setup/hold time math problems involving clock skew and jitter. They also ask to design FSMs for sequence detectors or vending machines on a whiteboard.
Google Silicon (Usually 4-5 Technical Rounds + 1 Googlyness/Behavioral)
Technical Rounds: Google leans heavily into Microarchitecture, RTL coding, and Problem Solving. You will be asked to code Verilog on a shared document (e.g., designing an arbiter, a synchronous FIFO, or a traffic light controller). Expect deep dives into computer architecture—specifically pipelining, hazards, and cache design.
Verification: If you lean toward the Verification/DV track, expect questions on Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in SystemVerilog and how to construct a testbench environment.

Part 2: The "No Blindspot" Technical Syllabus
To cover both the Google and Qualcomm JDs, you must master the following pillars. Do not skip the "Advanced/Interview Favorite" sub-bullets—these are where the actual interview questions come from.
1. Digital Logic & RTL Design (The Core)
This is the most critical section for both companies. You must be able to design and optimize logic circuits.
Combinational Logic: Multiplexers (build everything using MUXes), decoders, encoders, half/full adders, carry-lookahead adders, and multipliers.
Sequential Logic: Latches vs. Flip-Flops (transistor-level understanding of how a Master-Slave D-Flip Flop works).
Finite State Machines (FSM): Mealy vs. Moore machines. State encoding (Binary, Gray, One-hot) and state minimization.
Advanced/Interview Favorites: * Designing a sequence detector (e.g., "Detect 1011 with overlapping").
Designing a divide-by-3 or divide-by-1.5 clock divider.
Converting a D Flip-Flop to a T or JK Flip-Flop.
2. Static Timing Analysis (STA) & Clocking
You will not pass a Qualcomm or Google interview without mastering STA.
Setup and Hold Time: Definitions, equations, and calculating maximum clock frequency ($F_{max}$).
Clock Skew and Jitter: How positive/negative skew affects setup and hold equations. How to fix setup violations (reduce logic delay, increase period) and hold violations (add buffers).
Clock Domain Crossing (CDC): How to safely transfer data between two different clock frequencies.
Advanced/Interview Favorites:
Metastability (what it is, MTBF, and how to prevent it).
2-Flop / 3-Flop synchronizers for single-bit CDC.
Asynchronous FIFOs: You must know the architecture, how empty/full flags are generated, and why Gray codes are used for pointer synchronization.
3. Computer Architecture (Crucial for Google & "CPU Design" at QC)
Pipelining: The 5-stage RISC pipeline. Understanding Structural, Data, and Control hazards.
Hazard Resolution: Data forwarding (bypassing), stalling (bubbles), and branch prediction concepts.
Memory Hierarchy: Cache architecture (Direct-mapped, Set-associative, Fully-associative). Cache misses (Cold, Capacity, Conflict). Virtual memory and TLBs.
Protocols (Bonus): Basic understanding of AMBA AXI/AHB or UART/SPI/I2C protocols will make you stand out.
4. Verilog / SystemVerilog HDL
Interviewers will ask you to write synthesizable code on the spot.
Synthesizable vs. Non-Synthesizable: Knowing what constructs actually turn into hardware.
Assignments: Blocking (=) vs. Non-blocking (<=). (Rule: Use <= for sequential, = for combinational).
Avoiding Inferring Latches: How incomplete if-else or case statements create unwanted latches.
5. CMOS IC Design & Low Power (Crucial for Qualcomm)
CMOS Basics: Pull-up (PMOS) and Pull-down (NMOS) networks. Sizing transistors for equal rise/fall times.
Power Dissipation: Dynamic power equation ($P = \alpha C V^2 f$), short-circuit power, and static/leakage power.
Low Power Techniques: Clock gating, power gating, multi-VDD, and dynamic voltage/frequency scaling (DVFS).
6. Verification (DV) & Design for Test (DFT)
SystemVerilog OOP: Classes, inheritance, polymorphism, and randomization (if applying for the Verification track).
Coverage: Code coverage vs. Functional coverage.
DFT Basics: What is a scan chain? What is Boundary Scan (JTAG)? What is BIST (Built-In Self Test)?
7. Software & Scripting (Mentioned in both JDs)
C/C++: Bitwise operations are heavily tested (e.g., "Write a C macro to toggle the nth bit" or "Count the number of set bits in an integer"). Basic data structures (Linked Lists, Arrays).
Scripting: Basic understanding of Python, Perl, or Tcl. You won't be asked to code complex scripts, but knowing why they are used (automating CAD tool flows, parsing logs) is necessary.
8. Analog & Mixed-Signal (Only if pursuing the QC Analog Track)
If you are aiming for the RF/Analog roles mentioned in the Qualcomm JD:
Network Theory: RLC transient analysis by inspection.
Op-Amps: Ideal vs. Non-ideal, common configurations, Gain-Bandwidth product, CMRR, Slew Rate.
Oscillators & PLLs: Barkhausen criteria. Block diagram of a Phase-Locked Loop (Phase Detector, Charge Pump, Loop Filter, VCO).
You are absolutely right to ask this. For core hardware roles—especially at Qualcomm, and for any physical design or custom silicon roles at Google—device physics is heavily tested.
If you are a Computer Science student, they might forgive a lack of deep transistor knowledge. But for core ECE and VLSI candidates, MOSFETs and CMOS fundamentals are "Do or Die" topics. BJTs are slightly less emphasized for digital roles but remain a favorite for analog/mixed-signal interviews.
Here is the highly detailed, "No Blindspot" syllabus for semiconductor devices:
1. MOSFETs (Absolute Priority - Do or Die)
Interviewers don't just want you to know the formulas; they want to see if you understand how a transistor physically behaves when you change its dimensions ($W$ and $L$).
Regions of Operation: Cutoff, Linear (Triode), and Saturation. You must know the exact voltage conditions ($V_{gs} - V_{th}$ vs $V_{ds}$) that push the transistor into each region.
I-V Characteristics: Know the current equations for the linear and saturation regions.
Second-Order Effects (Crucial for Modern Nodes):
Channel Length Modulation (CLM): Why doesn't the current stay perfectly flat in saturation?
Body Effect: What happens to the threshold voltage ($V_{th}$) if the source and body are not at the same potential?
Velocity Saturation: Why do short-channel devices deviate from the standard square-law current equations?
Subthreshold Leakage: Why does a transistor still leak current even when $V_{gs} < V_{th}$? (This ties directly into the low-power design requirements in the Qualcomm JD).
Parasitic Capacitances: You must know where the gate, source, and drain capacitances come from ($C_{gs}, C_{gd}, C_{db}, C_{sb}$), because these define the RC delay of your digital circuits.
2. CMOS Inverter (The Holy Grail of Digital IC)
Every digital interview eventually boils down to the CMOS inverter.
Voltage Transfer Characteristic (VTC): You must be able to draw the VTC curve from memory.
The 5 Regions of VTC: Understand exactly which region (Cutoff, Linear, Saturation) the PMOS and NMOS are in at every point along the VTC curve.
Noise Margins: How to calculate $NM_H$ and $NM_L$, and why they matter for chip reliability.
Switching Threshold ($V_M$): The point where $V_{in} = V_{out}$. How does sizing the PMOS larger or smaller than the NMOS shift this curve left or right?
3. BJTs (Important for Analog/RF Roles)
If you are applying for the Digital SoC roles, you only need the basics. If you are targeting the RF/Analog layout roles at Qualcomm, you must know these deeply.
Regions of Operation: Active, Saturation, and Cutoff. (Note: "Saturation" in a BJT means something completely different than "Saturation" in a MOSFET. Interviewers love to trick students with this).
The Early Effect: The BJT equivalent of Channel Length Modulation.
High-Frequency Small Signal Model: The Hybrid-Pi model ($g_m, r_\pi, r_o$).
Interview Favorite: Bandgap Reference (BGR) Circuits. Why do we use BJTs instead of MOSFETs to create temperature-independent voltage references? (Answer: Because the base-emitter voltage $V_{be}$ has a very predictable, complementary temperature coefficient).
4. Diodes & PN Junctions (The Foundation)
You won't get entire rounds dedicated to diodes, but they are used as stepping stones in written tests.
Depletion Region: How it forms and how reverse/forward biasing alters its width.
Breakdown Mechanisms: Zener Breakdown (tunneling, heavily doped) vs. Avalanche Breakdown (impact ionization, lightly doped).
5. The "Hire Me" Factor: FinFETs & Advanced Nodes
Since companies like Google and Qualcomm are designing chips on 3nm and 2nm nodes, showing awareness of modern transistor architecture makes you stand out from 99% of undergraduates who only studied planar devices.
Planar vs. FinFET: Why did the industry abandon flat (planar) MOSFETs? (Answer: To gain better electrostatic control over the channel and suppress short-channel effects/leakage).
Gate-All-Around (GAA): The evolution beyond FinFETs (nanosheets/nanowires). You don't need to know the math, just the concept.
How to study this fast: Skip the heavy quantum mechanics chapters in your textbooks. Focus strictly on Chapter 2 (Basic MOS Device Physics) and Chapter 3 (CMOS Inverter) in the book Digital Integrated Circuits: A Design Perspective by Rabaey. That will cover 95% of what Qualcomm and Google ask regarding device physics.

